# Fluff Date: 2026-03-09 12:33:56
<overview>
<p>The Maxim (I) Heavy Hover Transport represents Scarborough Manufacturers' answer to the growing demand for dedicated battle armor carriers in the Draconis Combine military. Introduced in 3060, the design sacrifices much of the original Maxim's heavy weaponry in favor of a significantly expanded infantry bay capable of carrying a full squad of battle armor troopers alongside conventional infantry.</p><p>The designation "Maxim (I)" distinguishes this infantry-focused variant from the combat-oriented models produced at the same Scarborough facility on Al Na'ir. While less heavily armed than its predecessor, the Maxim (I) fills a critical logistical role in combined-arms formations where rapid battle armor deployment takes priority over organic fire support.</p>
</overview>

<capabilities>
<p>The Maxim (I) trades the original's extensive missile battery for a more focused weapons suite designed around supporting its embarked troops. A turret-mounted Streak SRM-6 provides accurate close-range firepower, backed by a pair of extended-range medium lasers that offer ammunition-independent engagement capability. A TAG unit retained in the turret allows the crew to designate targets for nearby Arrow IV batteries and semi-guided LRM munitions, giving the transport indirect fire coordination ability that most APCs lack.</p><p>The expanded twelve-ton infantry bay is the heart of the redesign. The interior accommodates a full platoon of battle armor with room to spare, or can carry a substantially larger force of conventional infantry. ProtecTech 6 ferro-fibrous armor replaces the original ArcShield plating, providing improved protection at reduced weight. The same PowerTech 165 Highlift engine maintains the familiar 129 kilometer per hour top speed. The primary weakness remains the hover skirt, and the reduced weapons load means the Maxim (I) is heavily dependent on its embarked troops and supporting units for protection once the infantry has deployed.</p>
</capabilities>

<deployment>
<p>The Company Command variant formalizes field modifications that emerged during the late Civil War era. Twin C3 master computers and a Guardian ECM suite transform the Maxim (I) into a mobile command platform for combined-arms formations. The armor and weaponry remain identical to the standard infantry variant, preserving the vehicle's ability to transport battle armor troops while simultaneously providing electronic warfare support and C3 network coordination for an entire company-level formation.</p>
</deployment>

<history>
<p>The Maxim (I) owes its existence to one of the most embarrassing episodes in Scarborough Manufacturers' history. When the Draconis Combine Military Services actively sought contracts for a transport specifically designed to carry a battlesuit-equipped squad, Scarborough won the bid with a proposal to upgrade the proven Maxim chassis. The company invested heavily in the project, publicly demonstrating wider doors, specially designed handholds, and seats modified for armored troopers. The DCMS purchased the upgraded Maxim and began distributing it throughout the military.</p><p>The design flaw became apparent when a Smoke Jaguar Nova raided McAlister within a week of general distribution. The upgraded Maxim lacked the capability to carry an entire squad of battle armor without losing speed, a critical failing that the original marketing materials had obscured. Contrary to the company's claims, the transport could only carry three battle suits inside its bay during the actual demonstration while maintaining operational speed. Scarborough initially denied the problem and attempted a public display of the Maxim's capabilities, but the demonstration only confirmed the shortcoming. The company quietly returned to the drawing board, and the DCMS began modifying already-purchased transports in the field.</p><p>The Blackwell Corporation, manufacturer of the competing Bandit hover tank, seized the opportunity to embarrass Scarborough further. Blackwell launched an advertising campaign built around the slogan "Able to carry what we say it can," directly targeting the Maxim's failure to meet its specifications. Sales of the upgraded Maxim declined steadily throughout the late 3050s as units lost confidence in Scarborough's claims. The public relations damage extended beyond the single product, threatening Scarborough's credibility as a military contractor.</p><p>Scarborough's engineers eventually produced a properly redesigned transport that delivered on the original promise. The Maxim (I), released in 3060, featured a genuinely expanded twelve-ton infantry bay capable of carrying battle armor at full operational speed. The redesign stripped most of the heavy missile armament, retaining only a Streak SRM-6, a pair of extended-range medium lasers, and a TAG unit. This weapons reduction was a practical necessity, as the expanded bay consumed mass that had previously been allocated to ordnance.</p><p>The Maxim (I) found wide circulation with DCMS units stationed along the Federated Suns border, where the increase of battle armor troops in infantry regiments created constant demand for dedicated carriers. The anti-personnel variant of the earlier upgraded Maxim was forced out of production as demand shifted decisively toward battle armor transport. Scarborough retooled the Al Na'ir production line accordingly, with the infantry transport version replacing the combat-oriented upgraded Maxim. The fire-support variant continued in parallel production, mounting a single LRM-15 rack alongside the original pair of LRM-5s to provide dedicated long-range bombardment capability.</p><p>Field modifications of the Maxim (I) emerged during the late Civil War and Jihad eras, taking advantage of vehicle-compatible C3 field modification kits. Some units replaced the machine guns for a C3 slave computer, while others went further and stripped out the cargo space and TAG to install a C3 master. The most extreme field variant paired C3 master computers with other similarly modified hover tanks and VTOLs, creating ad hoc networked reconnaissance and transport lances. The Company Command variant formalized this concept with twin C3 masters and a Guardian ECM suite, serving as a mobile command node for combined-arms formations.</p>
</history>

